<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-855-194  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 855 194.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unix-based tool eases database normalization. (Six Sigma Case'sCanonizer) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Six Sigma Case Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Canonizer (utility program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsUtility ProgramsUNIXNew CompaniesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Unix-Based Tool Eases Database NormalizationandM;BELLEVUE, Wash.andP;  -- According to the founder of Six Sigma Case, aSeattle-area start-up, most database managers have heard of normalization andthink they should be doing it, but are not quite sure what normalization is.andM;Six Sigma Case has produced a Unix-based software tool called the Canonizerthat solves this quandary by automating database normalization, a painstakingprocedure commonly done manually or not at all.andM;Normalization refers to deliberate structuring of the database to reduce itto its most economical and stable form, according to Six Sigma Cade Presidentand Chief Executive Officer Hunter zuker.andM;Although normalization sounds like a common sense technique, it is far fromcommon in many companies, and the process of normalization does not oftenfollow the logic typically used in the construction of corporate databases,Zuker said.andM;For many companies, a database evolves as a means of recording data necessaryto the company's core business, such as orders for the company's products, hesaid.andM;Often, the databases will mirror the paper forms -- such as customer orderreceipts -- used in the data entry process.andP;  In this manner, databases canbecome cluttered with extraneous and redundant information, he said.andM;Normalization only occurs when the database becomes swollen with redundantinformation or when new information must be added to the database, accordingto Zuker.andM;&quot;In the past, normalization has had to be done by hand.andP;  It's a tedious job,&quot;he said.andM;The Canonizer does the task automatically, normalizing the data to theso-called third normal form, which is considered the most stable andeconomical level of normalization, Zuker said.andM;The Canonizer creates a standard SQL script for use with a variety ofUnix-based database management systems, including Oracle, Ingres, Informix,Sybase and Unify.andP;  The product runs on a number of Unix operating systems,including ATandamp;T System V, Xenix, SunOS and BSD.andM;A single-user license for the Canonizer is available now, priced at $995until Jan. 1.andP;  Afterwards, the single-user license will be priced at $1,295.andO;Additional user licenses are priced at $195 each.andM;Six Sigma Case Inc. is located at 14405 S.E.andP;  36th St., Suite 120, Bellevue,WA 98006-1515, (800) 827-4462.andO;</TEXT></DOC>